After the liberal international order
Cambridge—Many analysts believe that the liberal international order ended with China's rise and the election of Donald Trump as U.S. president.
But if Joe Biden defeats Trump in the November election, should he strive to revive it?
Perhaps the outcome is not as such, but he must find some alternative.
Critics point out that the U.S. order since 1945 was neither global in nature nor always very liberal, and this is correct.
It excludes more than half of the world (including the Soviet bloc and China) and includes many authoritarian states.
American hegemony is always exaggerated.
Nevertheless, the most powerful country must lead in creating global public goods, otherwise they will not be provided — and Americans will suffer as a result.
The current pandemic is a good example of this.
A realistic goal for the Biden administration should be to establish an institutionalized international system based on rules, with different member states participating in handling different issues.
Will China and Russia be willing to participate?
During the 1990s and 21st century, both countries were unable to balance U.S. power, while the U.S. pursued the pursuit of liberal values above the sovereignty of states.
The U.S. bombed Serbia and invaded Iraq without obtaining approval from the UN Security Council.
It also supported a "Responsibility to Protect" resolution passed by the UN General Assembly in 2005, aimed at providing protection for citizens suffering cruel treatment at the hands of their own governments —— the U.S. later used this principle in 2011 to justify bombing Libya to protect civilians in Benghazi.
Critics describe this record as the arrogance of post-Cold War Americans —— for example, when the NATO-led intervention in Libya ultimately led to a regime change, Russia and China felt deceived —— while defenders of the action describe it as the natural evolution of international humanitarian law.
No matter what, the growth of China and Russia's power more strictly limits liberal interventionist actions.
So what remains?
Russia and China emphasize the principle of sovereignty stipulated in the UN Charter, which states that a state can only wage war for self-defense or with the approval of the Security Council.
Since 1945, the use of force to occupy neighboring territories has been very rare, and when it does occur, it incurs high costs through sanctions (as seen in Russia's annexation of Crimea in 2014).
Additionally, the Security Council frequently authorizes the deployment of peacekeeping forces in troubled states, and political cooperation has successfully limited the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction and ballistic missiles.
The rule-based order dimension remains crucial.
Specifically in economic relations, the world needs to revise the rules.
Long before the pandemic, China's hybrid state capitalism supported an unfair mercantilist model, which distorted the functions of the World Trade Organization.
The result will lead to the decoupling of global supply chains, especially when national security is threatened.
Although China complains that the U.S. is blocking companies like Huawei from building 5G communication networks in the West, the U.S. position is consistent with sovereignty claims.
After all, China has restricted the operations of Google, Facebook, and Twitter in China for security reasons.
Negotiating new trade rules would help prevent the escalation of decoupling.
At the same time, despite the outbreak of this current crisis, cooperation in key financial areas remains very strong.
On the contrary, interdependence in the ecological field creates insurmountable obstacles in the face of sovereignty, because the threat is cross-border.
No matter how much economic globalization is challenged, environmental globalization will continue, because it is subject to biological and physical laws, which are unaffected by contemporary geopolitical logic.
The above issues threaten everyone, but no country is capable of solving them independently.
On issues such as the 2019 coronavirus pandemic and climate change, power also has what is called a positive-sum dimension.
Under such premises, merely thinking about exercising power over others is insufficient.
We must also think about exercising power in collaboration with other countries.
The Paris Climate Agreement and the World Health Organization are beneficial to us and to others.
Since Nixon and Mao met in 1972, despite ideological differences, this has not affected cooperation between China and the United States.
Biden's challenge is whether China and the United States can cooperate to produce global public goods while engaging in competition in traditional great-power rivalry areas.
The cyberspace is a new and important issue —— because it is partly transnational but also controlled by sovereign governments.
The Internet has already been partially fragmented.
Free speech and privacy rules for the Internet can be established within democratic countries, but these rules will not be recognized by authoritarian countries.
As suggested by the Global Commission on Internet Governance, if authoritarian regimes also wish to achieve connectivity, then certain rules prohibiting the alteration of the basic structure of the internet would also be in their interest.
But when they use proxies to conduct information warfare or interfere in elections (practices that infringe upon sovereignty), it is necessary to strengthen norms through rules such as those negotiated during the Cold War between the United States and the Soviet Union to limit escalation in maritime incidents (despite the continued existence of ideological hostility).
The United States and like-minded countries must publicly declare the norms they intend to uphold and establish the necessary deterrence.
Pursuing free values in cyberspace does not mean that the United States is unilaterally disarming.
On the contrary, the United States should distinguish between permissible public persuasion through soft power and secret information warfare as hard power, and it must certainly retaliate when the other side launches secret information warfare.
It would be allowed for Russia and China to publicly broadcast programs and radio, but secret actions such as manipulating social media to achieve unity are not permitted.
Moreover, the United States will continue to criticize these countries' human rights records.
Public opinion polls show that the American public wants to avoid military intervention but does not want to withdraw from alliances or multilateral cooperation.
And the public still values values.
If Biden is elected, the issue he faces is not whether to restore the liberal international order.
The issue is whether the United States can cooperate with its core allies to promote democracy and human rights, while simultaneously collaborating with a broader range of countries to manage rule-based international systems needed to address transnational threats such as climate change, pandemic outbreaks, cyberattacks, terrorism, and economic instability.
